<br>
But, more to the point, you are correct Kaerilla that it is extremely difficult to prove a lie.  Just ask Kenneth Starr -- everyone knew Clinton was lying but Starr couldn't prove it until Clinton finally admitted that he lied. Here are some ways though you can prove a lie:<br>
<br>
1.  Show private emails, statements, letters, etc., from Zilor that directly contradict another statement.  For example, an email from Zilor where he states &quot;I know I was kicked out of guild X but didn't want to admit that so I said I wasn't&quot; would be your smoking gun.<br>
<br>
2.  Hearsay testimony (for example from his wife) could be used to show the state of his mind -- i.e. that he knew the statement to be false at the time he made it.<br>
<br>
3.  Other direct evidence of behavior that indicates a direct contradiction to the statement.    This one probably doesn't apply to Zilor's situation but in some instances a person's conduct can indicate that they knew the statement at the time they made it was false.<br>
<br>
Perjury happens all the time.  You will notice, however, that perjury convictions are few and far between.  It's simply too difficult to prove to be worthwhile. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ufurtivus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Furtivus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(4/3/02 3:21:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1150.topic&index=220>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ....</span><hr size=1> To follow up on your specific example Kaerila you stated &quot;'I believe the sky is pink.'  Prove that to be a lie.&quot;<br>
